rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: This pitfall consists in creating an ontology element and failing to provide human readable annotations attached to it. Consequently, ontology elements lack annotation properties that label them (e.g. rdfs:label, lemon:LexicalEntry, skos:prefLabel or skos:altLabel) or that define them (e.g. rdfs:comment or dc:description). This pitfall is related to the guidelines provided in [5].
Ontology elements (classes, object properties and datatype properties) are created isolated, with no relation to the rest of the ontology.

This pitfall appears when any relationship (except for those that are defined as symmetric properties using owl:SymmetricProperty) does not have an inverse relationship (owl:inverseOf) defined within the ontology.
A relationship is defined as inverse of itself. In this case, this relationship could have been defined as owl:SymmetricProperty instead.
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Defining a relationship as inverse to itself

rdf:Description.oops:hasAffectedElement: There are elements following different naming conventions as for example: http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/QuantityKindDimensionVector_CGS-GAUSS http://qudt.org/schema/qudt/ScaleType
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology elements are not named following the same convention (for example CamelCase or use of delimiters as "-" or "_") . Some notions about naming conventions are provided in [2].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Using different naming conventions in the ontology
Missing domain or range in properties
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: Object and/or datatype properties without domain or range (or none of them) are included in the ontology.
A symmetric object property (owl:SymmetricProperty) is defined as inverse of another object property (using owl:inverseOf).
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Defining inverse relationships for a symmetric one

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: An ontology element (a class, an object property or a datatype property) is used in its own definition. Some examples of this would be: (a) the definition of a class as the enumeration of several classes including itself; (b) the appearance of a class within its owl:equivalentClass or rdfs:subClassOf axioms; (c) the appearance of an object property in its rdfs:domain or range rdfs:range definitions; or (d) the appearance of a datatype property in its rdfs:domain definition.
The domain and range axioms are equal for each of the following object properties. Could they be symmetric or transitive?
rdf:Description.oops:hasCode: SUGGESTION: symmetric or transitive object properties.

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology lacks information about equivalent properties (owl:equivalentProperty) in the cases of duplicated relationships and/or attributes.
